<!-- LEGACY -->\r
<section id="legacy">\r
  <div class="section-container">\r
    <div class="section-header reveal">\r
      <span class="section-label">Chapter IX</span>\r
      <h2 class="section-title">An Eternal Legacy</h2>\r
      <div class="section-divider"></div>\r
      <p class="section-desc">His memory lives not in stone, but in the hearts of a billion people</p>\r
    </div>\r
\r
    <div class="legacy-content reveal">\r
      <div class="legacy-quote">\r
        <p class="legacy-quote-text">"Chhatrapati Shivaji was one of the greatest national figures India has ever produced. He was a born leader of men, a reformer, and a great ruler. His personal courage was remarkable."</p>\r
        <div class="legacy-quote-source">— Jawaharlal Nehru, First Prime Minister of India</div>\r
      </div>\r
\r
      <p class="legacy-para">Chhatrapati Shivaji Maharaj's legacy transcends time, geography and religion. He proved that a small kingdom, with the right leadership and the will of its people, could stand against the mightiest empires on earth — the Mughal Empire, the Bijapur Sultanate, the Golconda Sultanate, the Siddi Navy, and even the Portuguese and British sea powers.</p>\r
\r
      <p class="legacy-para">He was not merely a warrior — he was a statesman, an administrator, a naval strategist, a linguist, and a philosopher of governance. His Ashtapradhan system, his revenue reforms, his treatment of women and prisoners of war, his respect for all religions — these were centuries ahead of their time.</p>\r
\r
      <div class="legacy-quote" style="border-left-color:var(--gold);border-right-color:var(--saffron);">\r
        <p class="legacy-quote-text">"The life of Chhatrapati Shivaji has been a source of inspiration to countless generations of Indians. He showed that it is possible to combine military genius with political wisdom, and personal bravery with administrative skill."</p>\r
        <div class="legacy-quote-source">— Bal Gangadhar Tilak, Father of Indian Nationalism</div>\r
      </div>\r
\r
      <p class="legacy-para">Bal Gangadhar Tilak revived the tradition of Shiv Jayanti (Chhatrapati Chhatrapati Shivaji's birthday celebration) in 1893 to use it as a unifying force for the Indian independence movement. Mahatma Gandhi, Subhas Chandra Bose, and countless freedom fighters drew inspiration from Chhatrapati Chhatrapati Shivaji's example. Today, the Indian Navy's motto — <em style="color:var(--saffron)">"Sha No Varuna"</em> — carries forward the naval tradition Chhatrapati Shivaji began.</p>\r
\r
      <div style="background:linear-gradient(135deg,rgba(255,107,0,0.08),rgba(212,160,23,0.08));border:1px solid rgba(212,160,23,0.2);padding:50px;margin-top:40px;">\r
        <h3 style="font-family:'Cinzel Decorative',serif;color:var(--gold);font-size:1.5rem;text-align:center;margin-bottom:30px;">जय भवानी! जय शिवाजी!</h3>\r
        <p style="font-family:'EB Garamond',serif;font-size:1.3rem;font-style:italic;text-align:center;color:var(--cream-light);line-height:1.8;">\r
          "He was a king, a warrior, a judge — but above all, he was a servant of his people. In an age of ruthless power politics, he chose humanity. In an age of religious persecution, he chose justice. In an age of despair, he chose hope — and called it Swarajya."\r
        </p>\r
      </div>\r
    </div>\r
  </div>\r
</section>

